<h2>The short version</h2>

<p>You can change your name in England and Wales <strong>for free</strong> using a deed poll you write yourself. You do not need a solicitor, you do not need a GRC, and you do not need to have started any kind of medical transition. You can do it today.</p>

<div class="callout callout-blue">
  <p><strong>Important.</strong> You do NOT need to pay for a deed poll. Websites that charge £10-50 for "official" deed polls are selling you a piece of paper you can make yourself for free. The law is clear on this.</p>
</div>

<h2>Your two options</h2>

<h3>Option 1: Unenrolled deed poll (recommended)</h3>

<p>This is what most people use. It's a simple document that states your old name and new name, signed by you and witnessed by two people. It is legally valid for updating all documents.</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Cost:</strong> Free</li>
  <li><strong>Witnesses needed:</strong> 2 adults who know you (not family members)</li>
  <li><strong>Time to complete:</strong> 10 minutes to write, then take it to organisations</li>
  <li><strong>Accepted by:</strong> HMRC, DVLA, banks, employers, universities, GP surgeries, passport office — everyone</li>
</ul>

<p>You can use the free template at <a href="https://freedeedpoll.org.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">freedeedpoll.org.uk</a>. Print it on plain paper, sign it with your witnesses, done.</p>

<h3>Option 2: Statutory declaration</h3>

<p>A statutory declaration is a sworn legal statement made in front of a solicitor or commissioner for oaths. It carries slightly more legal weight but is not required for most purposes.</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Cost:</strong> £5-10 (solicitor's witnessing fee)</li>
  <li><strong>When you might need it:</strong> Some organisations (rarely) ask for a statutory declaration instead of a deed poll. The passport office accepts either.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What to update (and in what order)</h2>

<p>Once you have your deed poll, update documents in roughly this order:</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Bank accounts</strong> — take your deed poll to your branch. Most update within a few days.</li>
  <li><strong>GP surgery</strong> — ask reception to update your name. They can also update your gender marker on NHS records (this does NOT require a GRC).</li>
  <li><strong>HMRC</strong> — call or write to update your tax records. You'll need your National Insurance number.</li>
  <li><strong>DVLA</strong> — update your driving licence. Send your deed poll with form D1. Free if only changing name.</li>
  <li><strong>Passport</strong> — apply for a new passport with your deed poll. Standard fees apply (£82.50 online, £93 by post). You can update your gender marker at the same time with a letter from your GP.</li>
  <li><strong>Employer</strong> — provide your deed poll to HR.</li>
  <li><strong>University / school</strong> — contact the registrar.</li>
  <li><strong>Utilities, subscriptions, etc.</strong> — most accept a scanned deed poll by email.</li>
</ol>

<div class="callout callout-pink">
  <p><strong>Tip from the community.</strong> Get multiple copies of your deed poll signed at the same time. Some organisations keep the original, and you'll want extras. 5-6 signed copies is sensible.</p>
</div>

<h2>Common questions</h2>

<h3>Do I need a GRC to change my name?</h3>
<p><strong>No.</strong> A Gender Recognition Certificate is a separate process for changing your legal sex on your birth certificate. You do not need one to change your name, your passport gender marker, your NHS records, or anything else listed above.</p>

<h3>Can I keep my old name for some things?</h3>
<p>Yes. A deed poll doesn't cancel your old name — it establishes your new name. In practice you can use whichever name you want in informal settings. Official documents should be consistent though.</p>

<h3>What if an organisation refuses my deed poll?</h3>
<p>They shouldn't. A deed poll is a legal document. If they refuse, ask to speak to a manager and reference the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/change-name-deed-poll" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GOV.UK guidance on deed polls</a>. In rare cases, a statutory declaration may resolve the issue.</p>

<h3>What about Scotland?</h3>
<p>Scotland uses a slightly different process — you apply to the National Records of Scotland. The principle is similar but the forms differ. See <a href="https://genderkit.org.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GenderKit</a> for Scotland-specific guidance.</p>

<h2>What the community says</h2>

<p>This is one of the most straightforward topics. There is strong consensus across every source:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Free deed polls are legally valid. Do not pay for one.</li>
  <li>Most organisations accept deed polls without issue.</li>
  <li>Banks and the passport office are occasionally awkward but ultimately comply.</li>
  <li>Getting multiple signed copies is universally recommended.</li>
  <li>Updating your GP records early is important as it affects all NHS correspondence.</li>
</ul>

